Meet Cody

4 steps

Embark on an exciting journey through this series of quests as we delve deep into the world of coding with the assistance of Cody AI. Whether you're an aspiring developer or an experienced one, Cody is here to simplify the coding process for you.

In this quest, we will first introduce Cody AI and how aspiring developers can use Cody AI to assist them in their development journeys! We will also configure the Cody VS Extension on the IDE and write a bubble sort algorithm effortlessly!

Tutorial Steps

Total steps: 4

  • Step 1: Hello Cody

    Introducing Cody - Your Virtual Coding Assistant

    Meet Cody, your next-generation virtual coding assistant, engineered specifically for developers looking to elevate their coding process. With Cody’s integration using Sourcegraph's advanced code graph, Cody brings precision, knowledge, and expertise to every line of code you write.

    What is Sourcegraph?

    Sourcegraph is like the Google of code search. Designed exclusively for developers, it offers a powerful platform for effortlessly navigating large codebases. No longer do developers have to grapple with the tedious chore of combing through vast snippets of code. With Sourcegraph, searching and understanding code becomes a smooth, streamlined process.

    For a deeper dive into Sourcegraph, you can head over here!

    At its core, Cody is like having a knowledgeable pair programmer by your side equipped with the following:

    • Deep familiarity with your codebase
    • Access to a vast repository of open-source code
    • Years of data training, honed to understand code intricacies

    With these core features, Cody offers the following developer-centric features to make the overall development experience even more seamless. Here’s how:

    • Autocomplete - Autocomplete in any programming language powered by LLM technology
    • Chat - Strike up a conversation with Cody and Cody will guide you with insightful responses
    • Built In Commands - Swiftly perform essential actions whether it's generating unit tests, code refactoring or creating documentation!

    Why Aspiring Developers Need Cody

    • Interactive Learning - Get immediate feedback and learn the best coding practices on the go!
    • Time-Saving - No more getting stuck on pesky bugs or errors for hours!
    • Boost Productivity - Focus on innovating and building, while Cody takes care of the repetitive and mundane tasks!

    With a better understanding of Cody, in the next step, we will begin to install and configure Cody on our device!

  • Step 3: Write a Bubble Sort Function

    In this step, we will write a bubble sort function leveraging the expertise of Cody!

    To begin, create a project directory by running the following command on your desired directory.

    mkdir cody_ai

    Next, navigate to the project directory and instantiate a new project folder titled bubbleSort_Function by running the following command.

    cd cody_ai && mkdir bubbleSort_Function && cd bubbleSort_Function

    Next, open the bubbleSort_Function directory on your VSCode! Proceed to run the following command to initialize a Node.js application!

    npm init -y

    Proceed to create a new file titled bubbleSort.js under the bubbleSort_Function directory and here’s how your file structure should look like!

    Before we dive into writing the bubble sort algorithm, here’s a beginner-friendly explanation on what bubble sorting is!

    Overview of Bubble Sorting

    Picture a row of numbered cards spread out before you, and your task is to line them up in ascending order.

    Enter Bubble Sorting, a classic sorting algorithm that's all about comparison and exchange. This sorting method involves continuously comparing pairs of adjacent cards, and if the card on the left has a higher value than the one on its right, they get swapped.

    This process repeats, causing the card with the highest number to eventually bubble up to the end of the row. Then, the second highest finds its place, and so on, until every card is neatly arranged in increasing order.

    Let's visualize this with an illustration of Bubble Sorting!

    Now that you have a better understanding of Bubble Sorting, let’s implement it in code!

    Let’s Start with an Array

    First, we'll begin with an array containing unsorted values. Our goal is to implement the Bubble Sort algorithm to sort these values. By the end of the process, our function will return an array that's sorted in ascending order.

    Copy the following code snippet and paste it into bubbleSort.js.

    let array = [5,3,6,2,10,1,9,4]
